===Etymology===
From {{etyl|enm|en}} {{term|sheren|lang=enm}}, from {{etyl|ang|en}} {{term|scieran|lang=ang}}, from {{etyl|gem-pro|en}} {{m|gem-pro|*skeraną}}, from {{etyl|ine-pro|en}} {{m|ine-pro|*(s)ker-||to cut}}. Cognate with West Frisian {{term|skeare|lang=fy}}, Low German {{term|scheren|lang=nds}}, Dutch {{term|scheren|lang=nl}}, German {{term|scheren|lang=de}}, Danish {{term|skære|lang=da}}, Norwegian {{term|skjære|lang=no}}, Swedish {{term|skära|lang=sv}}, Serbo-Croatian {{term|škare|lang=sh}} ("scissors"); and {{qualifier|from Indo-European}} with Ancient Greek {{term|κείρω||I cut off|tr=keirō|lang=grc|sc=polytonic}}, Latin {{term|caro||flesh|lang=la}}, Albanian {{term|harr||to cut, to mow|lang=sq}}, Lithuanian {{term|skìrti||separate|lang=lt}}, Welsh {{term|ysgar||separate|lang=cy}}. See also {{l/en|sharp}}.

